stylometry: Aggregate Planning is an optimizations model that attempts to meet the supply and demand of a particular product by varying the quantity/timing/etc. of different inputs and outputs. Thus it would allow a manager to see how to best meet the customer's needs while also satisfying the companys constraints of production. All inputs and outputs that would directly affect the product would need to be considered, such as workers availible, materials availible, etc. The main goal of aggregate planning is the maximize profits. An example of tradeoffs that need to be considered would be producing more than needed so as to cover demand versus keeping inventory low to minimize holding costs.
